<HEADLINE>
PRICES AT TAIWAN'S TOURIST HOTELS UP 4.3% IN Q1
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  May 30 (CNA) 05/30/07  19:39:30 (By Lilian Wu)
</P>
<P>
Prices at Taiwan's tourist hotels rose by 4.3 percent in the
first four months of this year, the Directorate General of the
Budget, Accounting and Statistics (DGBAS) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
DGBAS officials said that as of the end of April, there were 90
tourist hotels with 21,274 rooms, down 0.6 percent from the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Room prices at tourist hotels averaged NT$3,209 (US$97.24) in the
first four months of this year, up 4.3 percent from the same
period of last year. International tourist hotels averaged
NT$3,374 per night, while ordinary tourist hotels averaged
NT$2,237 per night.
</P>
<P>
Although the room prices rose, the occupancy rate slumped. It is
estimated that the average occupancy rate was 65.1 percent in the
first four months of this year, down 4.1 percentage points from
the same period of last year. Tourist hotels overall took in
NT$5.31 billion, down 0.8 percent from the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
The government is also assisting private guest houses to meet
minimum service standards, the officials said, saying that there
were 1,969 such guest houses with 7,854 rooms as of the end of
April, up 48.4 percent and 45.3 percent, respectively from the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the distribution of the private guest houses, Hualien
County accounted for most with 546, followed Nantou Country with
368 and Yilan County with 256. The three counties accounted for
60 percent of all hotels.
</P>
